<paragraph blockId="33.[125,1172,944,1260]" pageId="33" pageNumber="296">
<emphasis box="[125,310,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="296">Male terminalia.</emphasis>
Epandrium entirely separated laterally at mid-dorsal portion, with 14–16 setae near posterior to ventral margins (
<figureCitation box="[576,714,977,1001]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="33.[155,215,841,860]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,796]" captionTargetId="figure-258@33.[170,1128,133,805]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figure 18. Amiota (Amiota) nozawai Chen and Watabe, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 2 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657941/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="296">Figure 18A</figureCitation>
). Surstylus pubescent on lateral margin, not expanded at postero-ventral corner, with six long prensisetae on distal margin and a few thin setae on lateral and ventral margins. Anterior portion of hypandrium entirely thin (
<figureCitation box="[133,273,1074,1098]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="33.[155,215,841,860]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,796]" captionTargetId="figure-258@33.[170,1128,133,805]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figure 18. Amiota (Amiota) nozawai Chen and Watabe, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 2 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657941/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="296">Figure 18C</figureCitation>
). Parameres separated from each other, lobe-shaped, each with apical, longer, strongly sclerotized and small, lateral, slightly sclerotized processes and six sensilla on subdistal mesal surface (
<figureCitation box="[420,566,1139,1163]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="33.[155,215,841,860]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,796]" captionTargetId="figure-258@33.[170,1128,133,805]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figure 18. Amiota (Amiota) nozawai Chen and Watabe, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 2 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657941/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="296">Figure 18D</figureCitation>
). Aedeagus separated into one pair of small rods, pointed apically, medially each fused to base of paramere; outer membrane undeveloped (
<figureCitation box="[133,306,1203,1227]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="33.[155,215,841,860]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,796]" captionTargetId="figure-258@33.[170,1128,133,805]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figure 18. Amiota (Amiota) nozawai Chen and Watabe, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 2 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657941/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="296">Figure 18E, F</figureCitation>
). Ejaculatory apodeme: apical plate with four pits on each lateral margin; stalk thick, long (
<figureCitation box="[328,471,1236,1260]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="33.[155,215,841,860]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,796]" captionTargetId="figure-258@33.[170,1128,133,805]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figure 18. Amiota (Amiota) nozawai Chen and Watabe, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 2 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657941/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="296">Figure 18G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
